{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_delta","contentIndex":1,"delta":" flights. Despite the","partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my review of the arbitration record, I need to submit my council vote for deliberation round 2. Let me analyze the evidence and arguments:\n\nThe core issue is whether Iran's issuance of NOTAM A1010/26 constitutes a \"major closure\" of Iranian airspace as defined by the market rule. The NOTAM A1010/26 shows:\n- It is labeled \"AD Airport Operations\" and has the Q-code QFALC, indicating it's an aerodrome closure (airports) rather than an airspace closure (FIR).\n- It closes all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except a limited number that operate only from sunrise to sunset.\n- It requires new CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n- It suspends all previous permissions for all operators.\n\nHowever, during this same deliberation round, there appear to be mixed votes among the council members:\n- C1 voted \"not_demonstrated\" in round 2, focusing on the Q-code distinction (QFALC indicating aerodrome vs. airspace closure)\n- C4, C5, and C6 voted \"demonstrated\" in round 2, seeing the NOTAM as establishing a broad regional closure with limited exceptions\n\nThe market rule defines a \"major closure\" as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. While the NOTAM uses QFALC coding (for aerodrome rather than airspace), the actual operational impact closes significant portions of the western Tehran FIR with very limited exceptions. Although the Q-code analysis makes the case closer than it might appear at first glance, on balance of the evidence I agree with the majority of my fellow council members who determined this constitutes a major closure under the market definition - it has a very broad impact on operations in a maj